{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_016bq7DKrfkvJ2dN964FczhR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a request to write a test plan for a spreadsheet formula engine. I need to analyze each of the 10 behaviors and determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures.\n\nLet me go through each behavior using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework:\n\n1. **SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly**\n   - MOCK-MISS: Could mocks miss this? No, this is pure computation.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed.\n   - LLM-DEP: No AI involved.\n   - This is a unit test — testing the SUM function and cell value lookup in isolation.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.9, Integration: 0.05, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01\n\n2. **Cascaded references (B1 = A1*2, then C1 = B1+1)**\n   - MOCK-MISS: Could mocks miss this? Could mock B1's result and miss the cascading calculation. But the behavior is about correct cascading, which requires the evaluator to properly resolve dependencies.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed.\n   - This requires multiple cells to be wired together and computed in the right order. You need to test the entire formula evaluation engine's dependency resolution.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit** — but borderline Integration because you need to test the dependency ordering engine with multiple cells. However, it's still pure in-memory computation with no external dependencies.\n   - Actually, thinking more carefully: this tests that the formula evaluator correctly resolves B1, then uses that result to compute C1. It's not about external infrastructure, it's about the evaluator's logic for handling formula references. This is Unit-level — testing the evaluator's reference resolution and cascading logic.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.85, Integration: 0.10, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01\n\n3. **Circular dependency detection (A1 → B1 → A1)**\n   - MOCK-MISS: No, this is about the dependency graph logic.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No external dependencies.\n   - This is testing the circular dependency detection algorithm — pure logic.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.95, Integration: 0.03, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.00\n\n4. **VLOOKUP with exact match and error handling**\n   - MOCK-MISS: Not applicable; VLOOKUP operates on in-memory tables without external dependencies.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.90, Integration: 0.05, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01\n\n5. **IF with nested conditions**\n   - MOCK-MISS: No.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No.\n   - Testing IF function logic and condition evaluation.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.95, Integration: 0.02, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01\n\n6. **CONCATENATE with empty cell handling**\n   - MOCK-MISS: No.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No.\n   - **Minimum level: Unit**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.92, Integration: 0.04, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01\n\n7. **Cross-sheet references (Sheet2!A1)**\n   - MOCK-MISS: Mocking sheet lookups could mask failures in actual cross-sheet navigation.\n   - REAL-INFRA: Requires multiple sheets loaded in memory, but no OS/network involvement.\n   - Need to construct a workbook with multiple sheets and verify the formula evaluator resolves cross-sheet references correctly. **Minimum level: Integration** — wiring sheets together and testing sheet lookup logic is beyond unit scope.\n   - Though if sheet objects are in-memory and behavior doesn't depend on storage structure, this could be Unit. But real failures emerge when sheet lookup is broken or sheets aren't properly isolated. Testing actual workbook state with multiple sheets catches these issues better than mocking.\n   - **Minimum level: Integration**\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.60, Integration: 0.40\n\n, System: 0.05, Agentic: 0.03, Workflow: 0.02\n\n8. **Dependent formulas recalculated in topological order**\n   - Mocking the recalculation logic could hide real failures in how dependencies are ordered. This needs a full dependency graph with multiple cells to verify the propagation sequence works correctly.\n   - **Minimum level: Integration** — setting up interconnected cells and confirming they recalculate in the right order requires more than isolated function tests.\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.1, Integration: 0.85, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01\n\n9. **Undo restores formula text and dependent values**\n   - Mocking undo logic could mask state management or formula caching problems. This requires editing a formula, confirming the change, then undoing and verifying both the formula text and all dependent cell values return to their original state.\n   - **Minimum level: Integration** — testing the undo mechanism with actual workbook state is necessary, not just isolated function behavior.\n   - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.05, Integration: 0.90, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01\n\n10. **Save and load workbook preserves formulas and values**\n    - This requires actual file I/O — writing to disk and reading back to catch real issues like binary format bugs, endianness problems, or floating-point precision loss that mocks would hide.\n    - **Minimum level: System** — involves serializing the workbook to a custom binary format and deserializing it, with verification that no data or precision is lost.\n    - Probability distribution: Unit: 0.01, Integration: 0.05\n\n, System: 0.90, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.02\n\nNow I'll map these to the structured output format. Each behavior needs a behavior_id (1-10), description, minimum_level, justification explaining why that level is required, test_description detailing what gets verified, plan_consistent as a boolean, and level_probabilities that sum to 1.0.\n\nStarting with the first behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM(A1:A10)**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: This is pure arithmetic computation with no dependencies on other components or external systems\n- test_description: A unit test that creates cells A1:A10 with values, sets a cell to =SUM(A1:A10), and verifies the result equals the expected sum\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.92, Integration: 0.04, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula references**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: The formula evaluator's ability to resolve references and handle cascading calculations is a single-component concern without external dependencies\n- test_description: A unit test that sets A1=5, B1=A1*2, C1=B1+1, and verifies C1 evaluates to 11\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.85, Integration: 0.10, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 3: Circular dependency detection**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: Detecting cycles in formula references is a core computational validation that doesn't require multi-component interaction\n- test_description: A unit test that creates A1=B1, B1=A1, and verifies the system detects and reports the circular reference\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.88, Integration: 0.08, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP exact match and error handling**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: The VLOOKUP function operates on in-memory data structures with no external system dependencies\n- test_description: A unit test that builds a lookup table and confirms VLOOKUP returns matching values and appropriate errors for missing keys\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.92, Integration: 0.04, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 5: IF with nested conditions**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: Nested IF evaluation is pure conditional logic without external dependencies\n- test_description: A unit test that verifies nested IF statements correctly evaluate numeric comparisons and return appropriate string results\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.95, Integration: 0.02, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 6: CONCATENATE with empty cell handling**\n- minimum_level: Unit\n- justification: String concatenation and empty cell handling are isolated function behaviors\n- test_description: A unit test that joins multiple cells including empty ones and confirms the output is correct without unwanted blank artifacts\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.93, Integration: 0.03, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 7: Cross-sheet references**\n- minimum_level: Integration\n- justification: Resolving formulas across multiple sheets requires coordinating sheet isolation and navigation logic, which involves multiple system components working together\n- test_description: An integration test that creates a multi-sheet workbook, references a cell from Sheet2 in a Sheet1 formula, and confirms proper value resolution and sheet accessibility\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.15, Integration: 0.78, System: 0.03, Agentic: 0.\n\n02, Workflow: 0.02}\n\n**Behavior 8: Dependent formula recalculation in topological order**\n- minimum_level: Integration\n- justification: Testing the dependency graph engine's ability to propagate changes through multiple cells in the correct order requires coordinating the full recalculation pipeline\n- test_description: An integration test that establishes a dependency chain (A1 → B1 → C1 → D1), triggers a change, and verifies all downstream formulas recalculate in proper topological order\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.08, Integration: 0.87, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo restores formula and dependent values**\n- minimum_level: Integration\n- justification: State management across formula edits and undo operations requires coordinating the workbook state and undo stack together\n- test_description: An integration test that modifies a formula, confirms propagation to dependents, executes undo, and verifies both the formula and all dependent values return to their original state\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.03, Integration: 0.92, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.02, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n**Behavior 10: Save/load preserves formulas and values**\n- minimum_level: System\n- justification: Actual file I/O operations and serialization to the custom binary format can only be tested through real file system interactions, where precision loss or format bugs become apparent\n- test_description: A system test that creates a workbook with form ulas (including floating-point values), saves to disk in binary format, loads it back, and verifies all formulas, cell values, and floating-point precision are identical to the original workbook\n- plan_consistent: true\n- level_probabilities: {Unit: 0.00, Integration: 0.02, System: 0.95, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.02}\n\nReconsidering behavior 7 — is Integration truly necessary or could Unit testing suffice? The critical issue is whether mocking the sheet lookup function would mask real failures. Actual problems could include incorrect sheet name resolution, exceptions thrown during lookup, parser failures on \"Sheet2!A1\" syntax, or improper storage of sheet objects in the workbook. Unit testing with mocks might verify that a mocked sheet lookup works, but it wouldn't catch issues with how sheets are actually stored or referenced within the workbook structure. Integration testing is needed to validate the full sheet resolution mechanism against actual workbook state.\n\nFor behavior 10, I'm questioning whether Integration with mocked file I/O is sufficient. The test involves saving and loading a workbook while preserving cell values, formulas, and floating-point precision. Mocked I/O could verify byte-level round-tripping, yet real failures might only surface with actual file system interactions — endianness problems, file permissions, partial writes, or OS-specific file handle behavior. Floating-point precision loss is more of a serialization algorithm concern than an OS-level issue, so Integration testing might actually be adequate here. The key is whether the binary format correctly preserves precision through the serialization process itself.\n\nBut the behavior explicitly states \"saving to disk and loading back,\" which suggests real file I/O matters. System testing is more appropriate since file I/O is OS behavior, and actual disk operations could reveal issues that in-memory serialization masks.\n\nFor behavior 8, I should examine whether it truly fits Integration. The behavior involves recalculating dependent formulas in correct topological order when a referenced cell changes.\n\nTesting this requires wiring multiple cells together with formulas, building out a dependency graph, and verifying the recalculation engine processes them in the right order. That's beyond what isolated unit tests can cover, so Integration applies.\n\nNone of these behaviors hinge on LLM output or real AI behavior, so Agentic testing isn't needed. They're all deterministic computations. Workflow also doesn't apply since there's no sequence of agentic steps involved.\n\nMy classifications are: Unit for SUM, cascaded references, circular dependency detection, VLOOKUP, and nested IF functions.  Unit for CONCATENATE as well. Integration covers cross-sheet references, dependent formula recalculation, and undo operations. System handles save/load functionality.\n\nFor the undo behavior specifically—restoring both formula text and dependent values after an edit—I need to verify state restoration across multiple cells and the undo stack. Mocking the