t spreadsheet engines, they're tightly coupled, so testing the evaluator naturally covers cascading. But if they're truly separate, then multi-cell coordination becomes an Integration concern. I think Unit is still appropriate since I'm testing the core evaluator logic, not orchestrating independent modules.\n\nFor behavior 8, the situation differs—this tests change propagation across cells when values update. Setting up the dependency chain, modifying A1, and verifying B1 and C1 recalculate in topological order requires coordinating multiple cells with the propagation engine. This feels more like Integration since it's testing how separate concerns interact rather than a single evaluator function.\n\nBehavior 2 is trickier. If I mock B1's return value when testing =B1+1, I might miss failures in how the formula evaluator resolves references or handles nested lookups. Using real cell objects instead catches these issues, but since there are no external dependencies and I'm still testing a single logical component (formula evaluation), most would classify this as Unit—though the boundary is less clear when multiple in-memory objects interact.\n\nFor the test cases, I'm categorizing them by what they actually require: pure computation stays Unit, formula evaluation with reference resolution stays Unit at 0.85 confidence, circular detection is Unit, and individual functions like VLOOKUP, IF, and CONCATENATE are Unit. Cross-sheet references move to Integration since they need multiple sheet objects, recalculation order is Integration because it requires change propagation, Undo is Integration for state management across cells, and Save/load is System due to file I/O. The confidence distribution reflects this: Unit gets 0.92, Integration 0.04, System 0.02, with minimal weight on Agentic and Workflow. = 1.00 ✓\n\nAll the probability distributions check out. Now I'll create the detailed descriptions for each category.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":nu